			<span class="authorname"><a href="http://mathiasbynens.be/">Mathias Bynens</a></span> said on December 11, 2009		</div>
		<div class="quote"><p>Jonathan, your code can easily be made into a jQuery plugin:</p>
<pre><code>  $.fn.slideShow = function(timeOut) {
   var $elem = this;
   this.children(':gt(0)').hide();
   setInterval(function() {
    $elem.children().eq(0).fadeOut().next().fadeIn().end().appendTo($elem);
   }, timeOut || 3000);
  };

  $(function() {
   $('.fadein').slideShow();
  });</code></pre>
<p>Now you can use something like this to invoke the slideshow on an element:</p>
<pre><code>$('.fadein').slideShow();</code></pre>
<p>As you can see, Iâ€™ve added a <code>timeOut</code> parameter. The default value is <code>3000</code> (I just took this from your code) but this can easily be specified:</p>
<pre><code>$('.fadein').slideShow(300);</code></pre>
<p><a href="//mathiasbynens.be/examples/slideshow">I uploaded an example of your script in this plugin format.</a>
</p>
